response:
First, we will count only the rectangles whose sides are parallel to the axes. We will pick two of the horizontal dots and two vertical dots to be the vertices of the rectangle. There are $\binom{4}{2}=6$ ways to pick two dots on the top line and $\binom{4}{2}=6$ ways to pick two dots on the second line, so there are $6\times6=36$ rectangles whose sides are parallel to the axes. Now, we will count rectangles whose sides are not parallel to the axes. By symmetry, it suffices to count the number of rectangles with a slope of $1$, and then multiply by $2$. We will highlight the horizontal and vertical lines in the diagram.$$[\begin{array}{ccc}
\text{divided}&\text{line}&\text{divided}\\\text{line}&\text{line 1}&&\text{line 2}\\\text{line}&&&\text{line}
\end{array}]$$To make a rectangle of slope $1$, we need to pick two horizontal lines and two vertical lines such that the difference in the horizontal coordinates is the same as the difference in the vertical coordinates. First, we choose the lower left vertex of the rectangle. There are $3$ choices for this. After we pick this vertex, there is exactly $1$ choice for the opposite vertex. Therefore, there are $3$ rectangles with slope $1$. By symmetry, there are also $3$ rectangles with slope $-1$, so there are a total of $6$ rectangles whose sides are not parallel to the axes. The total number of rectangles is $36+6=\boxed{42}$.</think> <answer>42</answer>

solution:
The graphs of both $\tan x$ and $\cot x$ have period $\pi.$  This means that the graph of $y = \tan x + \cot x$ repeats after an interval of $\pi,$ but this does not necessarily show that the period is $\pi.$

We can write
\[y = \tan x + \cot x = \frac{\sin x}{\cos x} + \frac{\cos x}{\sin x} = \frac{\sin^2 x + \cos^2 x}{\sin x \cos x} = \frac{1}{\sin x \cos x}.\]If $0 < x < \frac{\pi}{2},$ then $\sin x > 0$ and $\cos x > 0,$ so $\frac{1}{\sin x \cos x} > 0.$

If $\frac{\pi}{2} < x < \pi,$ then $\sin x > 0$ and $\cos x < 0,$ so $\frac{1}{\sin x \cos x} < 0.$

If $\pi < x < \frac{3 \pi}{2},$ then $\sin x < 0$ and $\cos x < 0,$ so $\frac{1}{\sin x \cos x} > 0.$

Therefore, the graph of $y = \tan x + \cot x$ also has period $\boxed{\pi}.$

The graph of $y = \tan x + \cot x$ is shown below:

[asy]import TrigMacros;

size(400);

real g(real x)
{
	return tan(x) + cot(x);
}

draw(graph(g,-3*pi + 0.01,-5/2*pi - 0.01),red);
draw(graph(g,-5/2*pi + 0.01,-2*pi - 0.01),red);
draw(graph(g,-2*pi + 0.01,-3/2*pi - 0.01),red);
draw(graph(g,-3/2*pi + 0.01,-pi - 0.01),red);
draw(graph(g,-pi + 0.01,-1/2*pi - 0.01),red);
draw(graph(g,-1/2*pi + 0.01,-0.01),red);
draw(graph(g,0.01,pi/2 - 0.01),red);
draw(graph(g,pi/2 + 0.01,pi - 0.01),red);
draw(graph(g,pi + 0.01,3/2*pi - 0.01),red);
draw(graph(g,3*pi/2 + 0.01,2*pi - 0.01),red);
draw(graph(g,2*pi + 0.01,5/2*pi - 0.01),red);
draw(graph(g,5*pi/2 + 0.01,3*pi - 0.01),red);
limits((-3*pi,-5),(3*pi,5),Crop);
trig_axes(-3*pi,3*pi,-5,5,pi/2,1);
layer();
rm_trig_labels(-5, 5, 2);
[/asy]

